<section xml:id="sec-intro-to-logarithms" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Intro to Logarithms</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>Logarithms are a kind of inverse of exponents.</p>
    
    <example>
      <title>Motivation for logs with base 10</title>
      <p>Consider these powers of 10,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>10^1\amp =10</mrow>
        <mrow>10^2\amp =100</mrow>
        <mrow>10^3\amp =1000</mrow>
        <mrow>10^4\amp =10000</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>These tell you that 10 to an exponent gives a number. Now reverse the question. Instead of asking what <m>10^3</m> equals, ask: <m>10</m> to what power equals <m>1000</m>? Since <m>10^3=1000</m>, the answer is 3.</p>
      <p>Logarithms are a shorthand for this reverse question. By definition, <m>\log_{10}(x)</m> (read this as <q>log base 10 of <m>x</m></q>) means the exponent you put on 10 to get <m>x</m>. Intuitively, <m>\log_{10}{x}</m> is the number of 10s you need to multiply in order to get <m>x</m>. So, for example,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\begin{array}{lcl}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp  \text{means...} \amp  \\</mrow>
        <mrow>10^3=1000 \amp  \longrightarrow \amp  \log_{10}(1000)=3\\</mrow>
        <mrow>10^5=100000 \amp  \longrightarrow \amp  \log_{10}(100000)=5\\</mrow>
        <mrow>10^0=1 \amp  \longrightarrow \amp  \log_{10}(1)=0</mrow>
        <mrow>\end{array}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>In other words,</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Powers convert <em>exponents</em> to <em>numbers</em></li>
        <li>Logs convert <em>number</em> to <em>exponent</em>.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>In this way, logarithms are a kind of <em>inverse</em> of exponents.</p>
    </example>
    <example>
      <title>Approximating Logarithms</title>
      <p>We know that for the equation <m>2^x=8</m>, the answer is <m>x=3</m>, because <m>2^3=8</m>. However, what about the equation <m>2^x=13</m>? We know that <m>2^3=8</m> and <m>2^4=16</m>, so we expect that the solution <m>x</m> is between 3 and 4. Maybe a better guess is in the middle, like <m>x=3.5</m>. Here, <m>2^{3.5} \approx 11.3</m>. Using logarithms, we can say that the exact answer is <m>\log_{2}{13}</m> (read as <q>log base 2 of 13</q>), which means the exponent you must put on 2 to get 13. With a calculator, we can find this to be about 3.7004. This means that <m>2^{3.7004} \approx 13</m>.</p>
    </example>
    
    <example>
      <title>Exact Logarithm Examples</title>
      <p>Similarly,</p>
      <ul>
        <li><m>\log_{4} 64 = 3</m>, because <m>4^3=64</m>.</li>
        <li><m>\log_{10}1000000 = 6</m>, because <m>10^6=1000000</m>.</li>
        <li><m>\log_{1/2}\brac{\frac{1}{8}}=3</m>, because <m>\brac{\frac{1}{2}}^3 = \frac{1}{8}</m></li>
      </ul>
    </example>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsection-logarithms">
    <title>Logarithms</title>
    <definition>
      <p>The <term>logarithm base b of a</term>, denoted by <m>\log_{b}a</m>, is the exponent that <m>b</m> must be raised to, to get <m>a</m>. In other words,</p>
      <me>
        \boxed{\log_{b}a = c \quad \text{is equivalent to} \quad b^c = a}
      </me>
    </definition>
    
    <image width="50%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[&gt;=Stealth,thick,scale=0.6]
        % tighter spacing
        \node[scale=2] (log) {$\log_{b}$};
        \node[scale=2,right=-0.5cm of log] (a) {$a$};
        \node[scale=2,right=0cm of a]    (eq) {$=$};
        \node[scale=2,right=0cm of eq]   (c) {$c$};
        
        % point near the subscript b
        \coordinate (bsub) at ($(log.south east)+(-0.5,0.4)$);
        
        % top arrow: c -&gt; a (label "equals")
        \draw[very thick,-&gt;]
        (c.north) to[out=120,in=60]
        node[midway,above]{equals} (a.north);
        
        % bottom arrow: b -&gt; c (label "to the power of")
        \draw[very thick,-&gt;]
        (bsub) to[out=-20,in=-120,looseness=1.1]
        node[left,below]{to the power of} (c.south);
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    
    <p>The equations <m>\log_{b}a = c</m> (<term>logarithmic form</term>) and <m>b^c = a</m> (<term>exponential form</term>) are two ways of expressing the same relationship between the numbers <m>a, b</m>, and <m>c</m>.</p>
    <p>With the logarithmic form <m>\log_{b}a = c</m>,</p>
    <ul>
      <li><m>b</m> is called the <term>base</term> of the logarithm.</li>
      <li><m>a</m> is called the <term>argument</term> (the value inputted into the function).</li>
      <li><m>c</m> is the <term>logarithm</term> (since it equals the logarithmic expression).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>With the exponential form <m>b^c = a</m>,</p>
    <ul>
      <li><m>b</m> is also the <em>base</em>.</li>
      <li><m>c</m> is the <em>exponent</em>.</li>
      <li><m>a</m> is the result of the power.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Notice that the exponent <m>c</m> is equivalent to the logarithm above (since logarithms are an exponent), and that the result <m>a</m> is equivalent to the argument above.</p>
    
    <project>
      <title>Converting Forms</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Convert each logarithmic or exponential equation to exponential or logarithmic form.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log 0.1=-1</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>10^{-1}=0.1</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{5}3125=5</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>5^5=3125</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>8^0=1</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\log_{8}{1}=0</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>8^{\frac{2}{3}}=4</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\log_{8}{4}=\frac{2}{3}</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>9^{-1}=\frac{1}{9}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\log_{9}\brac{\frac{1}{9}}=-1</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_3{729}=6</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>3^6=729</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{\sqrt{3}}{3}=2</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\brac{\sqrt{3}}^2=3</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>3^{-2}=\frac{1}{9}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\log_{3}\brac{\frac{1}{9}}=-2</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{2x}{(x+1)}=3</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>(2x)^3=x+1</m></p></answer></task>
    </project>
    
    <p>Logarithms are a name for a certain exponent. In particular, <m>\log_b{a}</m> is the exponent to which <m>b</m> must be raised, to obtain <m>a</m>.</p>
    <p>When you see <m>\log{\text{something}}</m>, mentally translate into <q>the exponent you'd put on the base to get what's inside</q>.</p>
    
    <project>
      <title>Evaluating Logarithms</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Evaluate each logarithm.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{4}16</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>2</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{2}32</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>5</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{3}9</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>2</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log 10000</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>4</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_3{81}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>4</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{7}49</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>2</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{5}3125</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>5</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log 1000000</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>6</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{4}256</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>4</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{3}729</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>6</m></p></answer></task>
    </project>
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-logarithm-bases">
    <title>Logarithm Bases</title>
    <p>The two most commonly-used logarithm bases are:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Base 10, denoted by <m>\log_{10}</m>, called the <term>common logarithm</term>, which is used in many applied sciences.</li>
      <li>Base <m>e</m>, called the <term>natural logarithm</term>, which is often used in calculus.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>These are often denoted by simply <m>\log</m> and <m>\ln</m>, respectively. In other words,</p>
    <md>
      <mrow>\log{x} = \log_{10}{x} \quad \text{and} \quad \ln{x} = \log_e{x}</mrow>
    </md>
    <p>These two logarithms are included on most calculators. The natural logarithm is denoted by <m>\ln</m> because it is an abbreviation of the Latin term <q>logarithmus naturali</q>.</p>
    <p>In computer science, often log base 2 is used, or <m>\log_2</m>.</p>
    
    <remark>
      <p>Note that previously, functions have been mostly represented by a single letter, such that <m>f</m> for <m>f(x)</m> or <m>g</m> for <m>g(x)</m>. For logarithms, we use three letters <m>\log</m> to denote the common logarithm, and two letters <m>\ln</m> to denote the natural logarithm. In this way, <m>\log{(x)}</m> or <m>\log_2{(x)}</m> represents a function just like <m>f(x)</m> does. However, we often write logarithms without parentheses as <m>\log{x}</m> or <m>\log_2{x}</m>. If you have seen the trig functions like <m>\sin{x}</m> or <m>\cos{x}</m>, then <m>\log{x}</m> is a similar kind of notation.</p>
      <p>If there are more than one term inside the logarithm, then we use brackets, such as <m>\log(x + y)</m>. Or, if there are a lot of factors, e.g. <m>\log\brac{\frac{x^2 y^3}{(x-1)^5}}</m>.</p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-basic-properties-logs">
    <title>Basic Properties of Logarithms</title>
    
    <example>
      <title>Base Examples</title>
      <p><m>\log_5{5}=1</m>. Also, <m>\log_3{3} = 1</m>.</p>
    </example>
    
    <theorem>
      <title>Logarithm of the base</title>
      <statement>
        <md>
          <mrow>\boxed{\log_{b}b = 1} \qquad \text{"log base $b$ of $b$ is 1"}</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>Because the exponent you need to put on <m>b</m> to get <m>b</m> is 1.</p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    
    <example>
      <title>Base 1 Examples</title>
      <p><m>\log_{3}{1}=0</m>. Also <m>\log_8{1}=0</m>.</p>
    </example>
    
    <theorem>
      <title>Logarithm of 1</title>
      <statement>
        <md>
          <mrow>\boxed{\log_{b}1 = 0} \qquad \text{"log base $b$ of 1 is 0"}</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>Because the exponent you need to put on <m>b</m> to get 1 is 0.</p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-evaluating-logs">
    <title>Evaluating Logarithms (By Hand)</title>
    
    <project>
      <title>Practice Evaluating Logarithms</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Evaluate each logarithm.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{7}\sqrt{7}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\frac{1}{2}</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{2}\brac{\frac{1}{2}}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>-1</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{\sqrt{2}}4</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>4</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{6}\brac{\frac{1}{216}}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>-3</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log{0.001}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>-3</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{4}\brac{\frac{1}{32}}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>-\frac{5}{2}</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{3}\sqrt{3}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\frac{1}{2}</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_2{\sqrt{32}}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\frac{5}{2}</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{8}\brac{2\sqrt[3]{2}}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\frac{4}{9}</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{2}\brac{\sqrt[3]{4}}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\frac{2}{3}</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{3}\brac{3\sqrt{3}}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\frac{3}{2}</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{9}\brac{3\sqrt{3}}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\frac{3}{4}</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{5}\brac{\frac{1}{25}}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>-2</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{2}\brac{8\sqrt{2}}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\frac{7}{2}</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{\frac{1}{2}}16</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>-4</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{27}\brac{3\sqrt{3}}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\frac{1}{2}</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_{2}\sqrt[6]{32}</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>\frac{5}{6}</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_2(\log_3(\log_4{64}))</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>0</m></p></answer></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>\log_4(\log_2(\log(10^{16})))</m></p></statement><answer><p><m>1</m></p></answer></task>
    </project>
  </subsection>
  
</section>